eryshire, Wales"},"en":{"about 1270–":"about 1270–Deceased","1270–Male":"1270–Deceased","1280–1372":"1280–1372","1275–1305":"1275–1305","1295–Female":"1295–Deceased","1300–Male":"1300–Deceased","1302–Female":"1302–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1244–Male":"1244–Deceased","about 1270":"about 1270","1275":"1275","1295":"1295","1372":"1372","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1305":"1305","1302":"1302","Abt 1300":"about 1300","1300":"1300","1244":"1244","about 1302":"about 1302","about 1275":"about 1275","Wales":"Wales","Meifod, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Meifod, Montgomeryshire, Wales","Montgomery, Wales":"Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Llywelyn","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["(Welsh)  See  Llewelyn ."],"variants":[{"name":"Llewelyn","meanings":["Traditional: altered form (influenced by <i>llew</i> ‘lion’) of <i>Llywelyn</i>, an ancient name of uncertain derivation. It probably goes back to the Old Celtic name <i>Lugobelinos</i>, the first element of which is <i>Lugu-</i> (the name of a god;  see  Lleu  ); the second is a name-forming element found also in names such as <i>Cunobelinus</i> (<i>Cymbeline</i>). The name was borne by  Llywelyn ap Iorwerth  (  1173–1240 ) and his grandson Llywelyn ap Gruffydd (  d. 1282 ), Welsh princes who for a time united their countrymen in North Wales and led opposition to the power of the Norman barons in South Wales and the Marches."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Loving’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Morgan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of Welsh Morcant , traditionally a boy's name. In Britain since the late 1990s the name has become equally popular as a girl's name, perhaps adopted with conscious reference to  King Arthur's  jealous stepsister  Morgan le Fay . Elsewhere in the English-speaking world, especially in North America, where it also enjoys considerable popularity, it is used predominantly for girls."],"variants":[{"name":"Morcant","meanings":["Traditional: composed of an unexplained first element + a second representing the Old Celtic element <i>cant</i> ‘circle; completion’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Llywelyn ap Morgan was born about 1270, in Meifod, Montgomeryshire, Wales as the son of Morgan ap Gwynllyw. He married Jonet verch Rhys. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 4 daughters."},"et":{"about 1270–":"umbes 1270–Surnud","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1280–1372":"1280–1372","1275–1305":"1275–1305","1295–Female":"1295–Surnud","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1302–Female":"1302–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1244–Male":"1244–Surnud","about 1270":"umbes 1270","1275":"1275","1295":"1295","1372":"1372","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1305":"1305","1302":"1302","Abt 1300":"umbes 1300","1300":"1300","1244":"1244","about 1302":"umbes 1302","about 1275":"umbes 1275","Wales":"Wales","Meifod, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Meifod, Montgomeryshire, Wales","Montgomery, Wales":"Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1270–":"noin 1270–Kuollut","1270–Male":"1270–Kuollut","1280–1372":"1280–1372","1275–1305":"1275–1305","1295–Female":"1295–Kuollut","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","1302–Female":"1302–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1244–Male":"1244–Kuollut","about 1270":"noin 1270","1275":"1275","1295":"1295","1372":"1372","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1305":"1305","1302":"1302","Abt 1300":"noin 1300","1300":"1300","1244":"1244","about 1302":"noin 1302","about 1275":"noin 1275","Wales":"Wales","Meifod, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Meifod, Montgomeryshire, Wales","Montgomery, Wales":"Montgomery, Montgomeryshire,